CE-352
                             NETWORK ENGINEERING - I
                                    Taner Arsan, Associate Professor
                             (2022-2023 Academic Year // Spring Semester)
                                CCNA v7.02 / Semester I + Semester II
         Introduction to Networks (ITN) + Switching, Routing, and Wireless Essentials (SRWE)

Aim of the course: Introduction to Networks course introduces the architectures, models, protocols, and
networking elements that connect users, devices, applications, and data through the Internet and across
modern computer networks - including IP addressing and Ethernet fundamentals. By the end of the course,
students can build simple local area networks (LAN) that integrate IP addressing schemes foundational
network security and perform basic configurations for routers and switches.

One of the important goals of this course is to focus on experiment design as a process of planning an
experiment to meet specified objectives to measure a specific value/s.

Switching, Routing, and Wireless Essentials focus on switching technologies and router operations that
support small-to-medium business networks and include wireless local area networks (WLAN) and security
concepts. By the end of this course, students learn key switching and routing concepts. They can perform
basic network configuration and troubleshooting, identify and mitigate LAN security threats, and configure
and secure a basic WLAN.

Coordinator: Assoc. Prof.Dr. Taner Arsan

Catalog data: Network fundamentals, network protocols, network access, network layers, switched
networks, ethernet switching, , basic router configuration, inter-VLAN routing, wireless networks, routing
concepts, static routing, default routes. (3+0+2)

Outline of the Course:

 Chapter   Introduction to Networks                     Switching, Routing, and Wireless Essentials
    1      Networking Today                             Basic Device Configuration
    2      Basic Switch and End Device Configuration    Switching Concepts
    3      Protocol Models                              VLANs
    4      Physical Layer                               Inter-VLAN Routing
    5      Number Systems                               STP
    6      Data Link Layer                              Etherchannel
    7      Ethernet Switching                           DHCPv4
    8      Network Layer                                SLAAC and DHCPv6 Concepts
    9      Address Resolution                           FHRP Concepts
   10      Basic Router Configuration                   LAN Security Concepts
   11      IPv4 Addressing                              Switch Security Configuration
   12      IPv6 Addressing                              WLAN Concepts
   13      ICMP                                         WLAN Configuration
   14      Transport Layer                              Routing Concepts
   15      Application Layer                            IP Static Routing
   16      Network Security Fundamentals                Troubleshoot Static and Default Routes
   17      Build a Small Network                        -

        Ross, 4th Edition, Addison Wesley, 2007, ISBN-13: 9780321497703.

   •    Internetworking with TCP/IP, Volume 1 – Principles, Protocols, and Architecture, Douglas
        Comer, 5th Edition, Pearson, 2005, ISBN-13: 9780131876712.

   •    Computer Networks, Andrew S. Tanenbaum, 4th Edition, Prentice Hall PTR, 2002, ISBN 0-
        13-066102-3.

CE402
                                Heuristic Optimization
                                 (2022-2023 // Spring Semester)

                          Fabio Stroppa, Assist. Prof.               (Coordinator-Mentor & Instructor)
                          Gülsüm Yiğit                               (Teaching Assistant)


Aim of the course: This course is a full in-depth analysis of the basis of Artificial Intelligence. It will
introduce students to search problems and how to solve them, focusing on optimality. Students will
learn how to describe a well-defined formulation for a complex problem, design intelligent search
algorithms, solve well-defined problems using Artificial Intelligence methods, develop problem-
solving skills, and learn how to solve optimization problems in different fields and areas. The course
will only deal with single-objective optimization problems. (2+2+0)
Language of the course: Theory lectures are language free; laboratories will be done in C++ and
MATLAB. Students can submit their projects in any programming language they feel more
comfortable with (suggested C/C++/C#, Java, Phyton, MATLAB).

Outline of the Course:

1. Introduction to Search and Problem Solving: Definition of search, examples, types of search,
definition of heuristic, definition of optimization, scope of optimization, examples of applications for
optimization, search and optimization algorithm overview.

2. Computational Complexity Analysis (Recap from Data Structures and Algorithms):
Definition of complexity analysis, terms of expression, Big-O notation, Big-O mathematical
formulation, Big-O table, Big-O properties, Big-O examples, brute force, logarithmic complexity,
divide and conquer and binary search.

3. Graphs and Trees (Recap from Data Structures and Algorithms): Definition of graph,
examples, terminology (cyclic vs acyclic, connected vs disconnected, directed vs undirected, graph
representations (adjacency matrix, adjacency list), definition of tree, examples, terminology,
representations, space complexity.

4. Properties of Search Problems: Formulation, models, examples, state graphs and search trees,
dealing with cycles and redundant paths, generic tree search algorithm, measuring problem-solving
performances.

5. Uninformed Search: Definition of uninformed search, strategies, depth first search (examples and
performance), breadth first search (examples and performance), iterative deepening search (examples
and performance), uniform cost search or Dijkstra’s algorithm (examples and performance),
bidirectional search (examples and performance).

6. Informed Search: Definition of informed search, definition of heuristic, examples, strategies,
greedy search (examples and performance), A* search (examples and performance), admissible
heuristics, creating heuristics, trade-off heuristics, dominance, dealing with cycles and redundant
paths, consistency.

7. Constraint Satisfaction Problems: Planning and identification, standard search and constraint
satisfaction problems, examples (map coloring, n-queens, cryptarithmetic, sudoku), constraint graph,
varieties of CSPs, varieties of constraints, real-world CSPs, solving CSPs with standard search
formulation (BFS, DFS), backtracking search, forward checking, constraint propagation, arc
 consistency and AC-3 algorithm, limitations of arc consistency, minimum remaining values heuristic
(MRV), least constraining value heuristic (LCV), structure of problems and independent
subproblems, tree-structured CSPs and algorithm, nearly tree-structured CSPs, cutset conditioning
algorithm, tree decomposition, iterative methods and min-conflicts heuristic.

8. Introduction to Optimization and Local Search: Definition of optimization, local search
strategies (hill climbing, simulated annealing, evolutionary algorithms), types and properties of
practical optimization problems, mathematical formulation, steps in an optimization task, design
variables, objective function, duality principle, constraints, variable bounds.

9. Introduction to Evolutionary Computation: Definition of evolutionary computation, usefulness
of evolutionary computation, nature as an optimizer, evolutionary computation and nature, population,
genetics (genotype, phenotype), natural evolution (selection, crossover, mutation, survival of the
fittest), exploration and exploitation, flow chart of evolutionary computation techniques, pseudo-code
of evolutionary computation techniques, typical behavior of an evolutionary algorithm, convergence
plot.

10. Binary-Coded Genetic Algorithm: Representing solutions, walkthrough with real variables, data
structure of a chromosome, working principles through an example, observations on binary-coded
genetic algorithms.

11. Operators of Binary-Coded Genetic Algorithm: Selection (roulette wheel selection, stochastic
universal sampling, tournament selection, rank selection, random selection), crossover (single-point
crossover, n-point crossover, uniform crossover), mutation (local mutation, uniform mutation),
survivor stage (non-elitist methods, elitist methods), genetic algorithm operator interaction.

12. Real-Coded Genetic Algorithm: Issues with binary-coded genetic algorithm, representing
solutions, walkthrough with real variables, data structure of a chromosome, working principles
through an example, observations on binary-coded genetic algorithms.

13. Operators of Real-Coded Genetic Algorithm: Selection (roulette wheel selection, stochastic
universal sampling, tournament selection, rank selection, random selection), crossover (linear
crossover, blend crossover, simulated binary crossover, fuzzy recombination operator), mutation
(random mutation, non-uniform mutation, normally distributed mutation, polynomial mutation),
survivor stage (non-elitist methods, elitist methods).

14. Handling Constraints in Evolutionary Algorithms: Constrained optimization, type of
constraints, search space type, types of penalty methods, adding penalty to fitness, handling equality
constraints, death penalty, static penalty, dynamic penalty, adaptive penalty, superiority of feasible
solutions over infeasible ones (Powell and Skolnick’s approach, Deb’s approach).

15. Adversarial Search (Games): Tentative! How to get behavior out of computation, adversarial
games, types of games, deterministic games, zero-sum games, single-agent tree, value of a state,
adversarial game trees, minimax values, tic-tac-toe game tree, minimax algorithm (implementation,
efficiency, properties), resource limits, the importance of depth, evaluation functions (example for
Pacman), game tree pruning (alpha-beta pruning for minimax).

Projects:

Students will propose problems to be optimized and implement search algorithms to solve them.
Projects must be fully implemented by students without using built-in libraries.

There will be deadlines through the term for project submission. If a student misses any deadline, they
will not be allowed to do the exam and will immediately receive a failing grade.
 Grading:

Participation:                i.e., interaction and interest showed during lectures, participation will be
                              taken into account during grading to round-up borderline grades.

Oral Exam:                    project presentation + Q&A on projects and course content

Oral exams will be between May 15 and June 1. The calendar will be published as the end of the term
approaches.

Textbook:
   • S. Russel, P. Norvig. “Artificial Intelligence: A Modern Approach”. Pearson; 4th edition.
   • K. Deb. "Multi-objective Optimization Using Evolutionary Algorithms". Wiley; 4th edition.

Prerequisites:

   •   Having successfully completed “CE/CME/CMPE 242 – Data Structures & Algorithms” or
       equivalent course
   •   Be able to communicate in English
   •   Be able to write efficient code (C/C++/C#, Java, Phyton, MATLAB)
   •   Be familiar with numerical bases (binary code, hexadecimal code)
   •   Be able to evaluate computational complexity (both in time and space)
   •   Be familiar with the fundamental data structures and their implementation (e.g., dynamic
       arrays, linked lists, stacks, queues, priority queues)
   •   Be familiar with sorting algorithms (e.g., merge sort, quick sort, heap sort)
   •   Be familiar with the basics of statistics (probability)

Lectures:         Tuesday 09:00-11:00 (B203), Thursday 09:00-11:00 (Lab2)

Office hours:     Appointments through: https://fabio-stroppa.youcanbook.me/

Plagiarism:
Plagiarism is taking and using another person's thoughts, ideas, writings, images, or music as your
own, without acknowledging or giving appropriate references as to the source of those ideas and
expressions. In the case of copyrighted work, plagiarism is illegal. Plagiarism on the final project is a
serious offense: the student will receive an immediate failing grade for the class and their name
will be reported to the disciplinary board for more severe action. There are no exceptions to this rule.
If you are in doubt about the definitions of plagiarism, consult your course instructors.
General Class Rules:
Please turn off/mute all your electronic devices. You are expected to give your full attention to the
class. If the instructor realizes that the class is not paying attention, he will leave the class and the
students will be responsible for studying the part that was not explained in class. Lack of knowledge
of the academic honesty policy is not a reasonable explanation for a violation, so cheating will not be
tolerated.
Attendance Policy:
Attendance is highly recommended. Students with less than 80% of attendance will not be allowed to
participate to the exam and will receive a failing grade. Students who work in a company and cannot
attend the lectures must submit a letter from their company to be exempted from this rule; however,
missing lectures will harden the learning outcome. Students with health emergency will be excused
after the submission of an official medical report signed by their physician. Class overlap is not
considered as exemption.
 Students are expected to be on-time. Students that will arrive one minute after the class is started will
not be allowed to attend. Saying the phrase “the blue sheep is at the top of the hill” during lectures
will prove to the lecturer that you have read this syllabus, and this will increase your participation
level.
If no prior arrangement has been made and neither the instructor nor a substitute instructor has arrived
by 30 minutes after the scheduled start of class, students may leave.
Disclaimer:
The instructor holds the right to:
     • request a verbal examination about an assignment submission;
     • make changes on the grading percentages as needed with an announced update (usually to the
         benefit of the students);
     • ask a student to leave the classroom in case of misbehavior or silent attendance (e.g., the
         student sleeps or plays with the phone during the lecture);
     • not accept a student to the classroom in case of late show up;
     • leave the class if he realizes students are not paying attention to the lecture;
     • lower a student’s grade from a group work if the student cannot defend their contribution well
         enough;
     • lower a student’s grade if they cannot clearly communicate their answer; and
     • ask for mandatory exams reservations to participate to Live Projects and/or Oral
         Presentations, and do not accept students without reservation.
It is the student's responsibility to:
     • communicate clearly in English during an oral examination;
     • check the syllabus and the announcements on Khas Learn for any possible updates;
     • follow all explanations and instructions provided with the assignment(s);
     • turn in their answers without any academic dishonesty;
     • come to the lectures on time;
     • request further feedback within one week of grade announcements; and
     • be prepared for all class material during exams.

Below are the questions about Kadir Has University and asked by student to the Buddy. Below, questions include questions and their answers about the accommodation in Kadir Has University. 

Student: How is the housing scholarship, do I need to fill out anything for it?
Buddy: Successful in the university entrance exams held by ÖSYM and out of the top 3000 and outside of Istanbul. It is a dormitory scholarship provided to students who come and unroll in KHAS. After the list comes to us from ÖSYM, we are looking for you and we are giving you the necessary information about accommodation.

Student: Does the school have contracted dormitories?
Buddy: Our university did not have a contracted dormitory.

Student: What districts are close to our school?
Buddy: Fatih, Sisli, Eminonu, Mecidiyekoy, Besiktas.

Student: Which dormitories are close to the school?
Buddy: I cannot say a specific any dormitory. However, you can check out any of them from Fatih, Besiktas, Sisli, Eminonu or Mecidiyekoy.

Student: Does the school have a hostel?
Buddy: No, the school has not any hostel. However, you can find dormitories.

Kadir Has University                                                          2022-2023

             CE348 - Formal Languages and Automata Theory
                                       Instructor : İLKTAN AR
E-Mail:ilktana@khas.edu.tr                                                Lecture:FR:09:00-12:00(CBL-B-522)
Phone:+90 (212) 533 65 32 (1206)                                            Office Hours:Friday 14:00-16:00,
TA:Batuhan Yıldırım                                                                Lab. D (network lab, A/023)
E-mail:batuhan.yildirim@khas.edu.tr                                                 Local / ECTS Credit:3 /5
                                                                                    Course Type:Compulsory
                                                                             Withdraw:07 MAR-05 MAY 2023

Textbook / Readings
Introduction to the Theory of Computation, 3rd Edition (2nd edition is also acceptable), Michael Sipser, Cengage
Learning, 2013.

Other Materials
Introduction to Automata Theory, Languages, and Computation, 3rd Edition, John E. Hopcroft, Rajeev Motwani,
Jeffrey D. Ullman, Pearson, 2007 Class notes.

Course Objectives

The emphasis of is on learning three basic concepts: what is computation, what can be computed, what can not
be computed? The course topics are mathematical by nature and proofs are presented throughout. Skills in
reasoning about computation and constructing proofs should be developed.

Course Contents

Introduction to the main concepts of computation. The connection between problems and languages is
established. Languages are classified (regular, context-free etc) according to how "difficult" they are and
corresponding to each language class a model of computation is described. Each model is represented via a
corresponding machine (automaton).

Learning Outcomes

1- Recognizing regular languages using regular expressions and finite automata, and proving nonregularity.
2- Ability to design context-free grammars and pushdown automata for context free languages, and to prove
non-context-freeness of such a language.
3- Understanding the relationship between decision problems and languages.

Learning Activities and Teaching Methods
Lecture, Classroom discussions.

About The Computer Engineering Program
Information on the Institution
Department of Computer Engineering was established in1997 under the Faculty of Engineering which later evolved to the Faculty of Engineering and Natural Sciences. The first students were accepted in 1999 and the first B.S. degrees were awarded in 2003.

Qualification Awarded / Level of Qualification
Upon successful completion of the program, students will be awarded with Bachelor of Science in Computer Engineering (The Qualifications Frameworks in the European Higher Education Area (QF-EHEA): Level 1, European Qualifications Framework (EQF): Level 6 )

Admission Requirements
Applicants should obtain the required scores from Transition to Higher Education Examination (YGS), First Cycle Placement Test (LYS/MF 4), and Direct Transfer Test (DGS). Placements are centrally organized by Student Selection and Placement Center (ÖSYM). International students applying for the program must follow the admissions criteria determined by Kadir Has University. Students can transfer into the program by following Kadir Has University regulations on the basis concerning horizontal transfer. (Furher information: http://www.khas.edu.tr)

Recognition of Prior Learning
Students may be exempted from some of the courses they have succeded in a previously attended programme, if they have not been counted towards a degree already, in view of the Exemption Regulations of Kadir Has University. Courses taken by students coming with ?Direct Transfer Test? (DGS) from an associate degree program will also be evaluated based on Exemption Regulations of Kadir Has University.

Graduation Requirements
Students are required to successfully complete all courses in the curriculum accepted by the Senate (240 ECTS Credits) and have a minimum Cumulative Grade Point Average of 2.00/4.00. In addition, each student must complete 40 days of compulsory internship.

Definition of the Program
The underlying philosophy of the programme is to educate engineers who are equipped with up-to-date knowledge, who can react to needs of the professional sector and academic life and can produce know-how. The students are specializing on software engineering, computer network planning and mobile appolications. Besides, courses required for Cisco Certified Network Associate (CCNA), Oracle Application Development, Microsoft CRM Dynamics, EMC Proven Professional sertificates are embedded in the curriculum.

Program Outcomes
1- Ability to apply the knowledge of mathematics, science and engineering to model and solve problems in computer engineering
2- Ability to understand and apply discrete mathematics,
3- Ability to define complex engineering problems, collect, analyze data,  analyze problems and develop models and implement solutions  for the engineering problems,
4- Ability to analyze, design and manage the hardware/software computer system requirements  with limited resources and conditions by modern engineering principles,
5- Ability to use modern engineering techniques, tools and information technologies and develop software equipment and software,
6- Ability to conduct lab experiments by using computers and to have the ability of collecting data, analyze, interpret data and to solve engineering problems,
7- Ability to work on multidisciplinary topics with teams as well as individually,
8- Ability to communicate  in Turkish and English very well in the written and oral form,
9- Ability to follow international works in his or her field,
10- Ability to follow technological innovations and to engage in life-long learning in order to adapt himself/herself to the changing conditions of the future with professional and ethical responsibility,
11- Ability to make a difference about the project management, entrepreneurship and quality control,
12- An understanding of current/contemporary issues and impact of engineering solutions in legal and ethical levels
Occupational Profiles of Graduates
Graduates can be employed in various areas of computer engineering such as those including project activities in, for example, Android and Apple iOS based mobile application development, customer relationship management, enterprise resource planning, embedded systems, computer network infrastructures and database application development.

Access to Further Studies
Upon successful completion of the undergraduate program, candidates can apply to graduate programs to pursue a masters' degree or, depending on their GPA, a doctoral degree.

Assessment and Grading
See "Regulations for Undergraduate Degree Programs" at Kadir Has University (https://my.khas.edu.tr/uploads/files/mevzuat/undergraduate-education-regulations.pdf)

Mode of Study / Language of Instruction
Full-time / English

Contact Address and Information
Doç. Dr. Taner Arsan (Head of the Department) 0212 533 6532 ext. 1405, arsan@khas.edu.tr

Evaluation Questionnaires
Course and Instructor Evaluation Questionnaire, Graduation Questionnaire, Satisfaction Questionnaire

International Cooperation
Exchange (North America, Europe, Asia), double degree (Montana State University, Purdue University at Indianapolis) and ERASMUS (13 universities in nine countries) programmes (see https://international.khas.edu.tr/)

Below are the questions about Kadir Has University and asked by student to the Buddy. Below, questions include questions and their answers about the campus life in Kadir Has University. 

Student: Can you talk about active clubs?
Can you talk about active clubs?
Buddy: Our all clubs are active.

Student: Is the prep school on the Cibali campus?
Buddy: Yes it is.
 
Student: How much does he go to meals at school in a day?
Buddy: For now it is 35 TL.

Student: Does the school have a football team?
Buddy: Yes, it has.

Student: Will I be a stranger on campus? Can you talk about the students at the school in general?
Buddy: You will not be a stranger. You can talk whoever you want.

Student: Is it easy to adapt to school?
Buddy: Yes, trust me it is really easy. 

Student: Is there a communication channel where we can follow the activities of the school?
Buddy: Yes, it is.

Student: Is participation in the orientation program compulsory?
Buddy: No, it's not mandatory, but it would be nice if you could join.

Student: Will there be 2 different orientations? (Are the preparatory orientation and the undergraduate orientation separate?)
Buddy: No, they have the same orientation day.

Student: How to register for clubs?
Buddy: All clubs set up stands in Hall A during the first week of school. You can go and talk to them and become a member.	

Student: Are there clubs on learning a new language?
Buddy: No, but you can take a language course for a learn new language.

Student: How are the prices and quality of the cafeteria? Are the surrounding businesses good?
Buddy: The quality of the cafeteria is debatable, for now 3 cups of food are 35 TL. But if you don't like it, there is more than one food place within a maximum of five minutes from the school. It's up to you to choose the one that fits your budget. I adore the toaster Albay, which is behind the school.
 
Student: Which cafes are in our school?
Buddy: Two different dining hall, Starbucks and Espresso Lab.

Student: Does the school have ring services?
Buddy: No, the school has not any ring service unfortunately.

Student: Which public transport is close to the school?
Buddy: Subway, bus stop, Marmaray and tram.

Student: Is our library big?
Buddy: Yes, the library has many different quiet zones, you can sit in a place that suits you.

Student: How is the campus size and what can we do inside?
Buddy: You can study in the huge library, you can drink coffee in Starbucks or Espresso Lab, you can sleep or lie on comfy sofas.

Student: Extra sports at school, etc. Can I participate in activities?
Buddy: Yes you can participate to any sport team. Especially sailing team is much famous.

Student: Faculty WhatsApp groups have/will be established?
Buddy: Students open WhatsApp groups among themselves. When you join the class, you can also be involved by communicating.

Student: There are people you know for computer engineering, how do they think about the department? 
Buddy:Yes I know. They say it is quite hard but if you work properly it will be good for anyone.

Student: Does the school have social activities? How is the social life?
Buddy: We have so many school club for social activities. You can find all clubs from this link: https://bologna.khas.edu.tr/32/ogrenci-kulupleri

Student: Will there be a campus promotion event?
Buddy: Yes, you will have an orientation day.

Student: What is done on orientation/adaptation days?
Buddy: You can check out or academic calendar. https://akademiktakvim.khas.edu.tr/lisans

cfb9df05-180b-47e1-ba49-6512abc98b4f.text:
Below are the questions about Kadir Has University and asked by student to the Buddy. Below, questions include questions and their answers from the English exam in Kadir Has University. 

Student: How many questions are there in the exam?
Buddy: Language Placement and Proficiency Exam (LPPE) Stage 1 consists of 100 multiple choice questions and lasts for 90 minutes. 

Student: What is the difficulty level of the exam?
Buddy: Its difficulty depends on your language knowledge.

Student: Are there sessions on different dates?
Buddy: Yes. You will receive an e-mail about it. Do not worry.

Student: Is it compulsory to take the exam?
Buddy: Yes, it is compulsory. Otherwise you will begin from the lowest stage.

Student: How many stages will the exam have?
Buddy: There are just two stages.
 
Student: Is TOEFL score accepted?
Buddy: Yes, it is accepted.

Student: When are the results of the English exam announced?
Buddy: You should keep track of the academic calendar.

Student: What happens if we get 60 or less on the second exam?
Buddy: You will fail from the prep exam and will begin from prep class.

Student: Is there a switch between tracks?
Buddy: Yes there is. You should talk it during your prep class is going on with your teachers.

Student: I was at B2 level, do you think I can pass?
Buddy: I don't know, you too won't know until you try.

Student: Wouldn't it be better for us if we didn't take the exam and start from 0?
Buddy: No, believe me it is not better. At least it's better for you to determine your level in this regard.

Student: If I start from Track 1, do I have to stay in the extended spring term?
Buddy: Extended spring term is not obligatory for any student, but it is highly recommended to a Track 1 student to take it.

Student: What should I bring with me to the exam?
Buddy: You should just bring your pencil and eraser.

Student: DO I NEED TO REGISTER FOR THE EXAM?
Buddy: No, you do not have to register for it.

Student: On which campus will the exam be held?
Buddy: It will be hold in Cibali Campus.
 
Student: What are the questions in the LPPE second phase?
Buddy: LPPE Stage 2 consists of Listening, Writing, and Reading sections. For further information please visit: https://sfl.khas.edu.tr/khas-ingilizce-seviye-tespit-ve-yeterlilik-sinavi/

Student: Is the English exam grammar or vocabulary weighted?
Buddy: Their weights are equal.

Student: If I want to start from the lowest level, is it okay if I don't take the exam?
Buddy: Yes, but I recommend you to join the exam.

Student: If we pass the 1st stage successfully, is it mandatory to enter the 2nd stage?	
Buddy: Yes, if you will not attend the second stage, then your level is determined by it.

Student: What is the percentage of passing the 2nd stage of the preparatory exam?
Buddy: If you get 60 out of 100, you successfully pass the LPPE Stage 2

Student: Are the exams face-to-face or online?	
Buddy: All exams are made face-to-face.

Student: What is a passing grade?
Buddy: It is 60/100.	

Student: Will the two exams be written?
Buddy: Yes. 

Student: Will there be speaking in the exam?
Buddy: Yes, in the second stage of the exam you will have a speaking exam.	

Student: How long does the first stage of the preparatory exam take and how many questions does it consist of?
Buddy: Language Placement and Proficiency Exam (LPPE) Stage 1 consists of 100 multiple choice questions and lasts for 90 minutes. 	

Student: What kind of questions does the first stage of the preparatory exam consist of?
Buddy: It is a grammar and vocabulary based test.

Student: What is the level of the first stage of the preparatory exam?
Buddy: In the first stage you will only be tested on basic English.

Student: Will there be speaking in the second stage of the exam?
Buddy: Yes, in the second stage of the exam you will have a speaking exam.

078cdf58-06b0-40e3-b91f-7d9356aa1c2e.text:
Below are the questions about Kadir Has University and asked by student to the Buddy. Below, questions include questions and their answers about the financial affairs, registration and payments in Kadir Has University. 

Student: Will the payment be made on the day of registration or just paperwork?
Buddy: If you don't have a full-scholarship, you have to pay depends on which type of payments you have chosen.

Student: Which banks are you contracted with?
Buddy: Akbank and DenizBank.

Student: How can we make an online payment in cash or in with credit?
Buddy: You can pay it via sparks system.

Student: Is there a problem if the payment is online?
Buddy: No, you can do it online.

Student: Do we have to deposit the money in advance for face-to-face registration?
Buddy: If you are paying with credit, you have to pay the first credit. It does not matter if your registration is online or face to face.

Student: Is there a scholarship that can contribute to the tuition fee?
Buddy: Yes, you can check out this website for detailed information: https://aday.khas.edu.tr/burslar

Student: Can the tuition fee be paid in discount?
Buddy: No.

Student: Are there any scholarship cuts in prep school?
Buddy: No.

Student: Can we come to school and pay the money in online payment, what are the payment methods?

Student: Can a family member make the payment?
Buddy: Yes.

Student: Is it possible to make discount / how is it done?
Buddy: Besides your scholarship, there are no any discount.

Student: Do we pay tuition when we come to school?
Buddy: Yes, you should do it anytime at registration day. 

Student: Can I make the payment after my registration is created?
Buddy: Yes.

Student: Receipt of payment etc. in registration documents. It should be, but I couldn't find an iban on the website where I can pay.

Student: How are the payment methods?
Buddy: You can pay with credit as 9 credit for entire year, or you can pay entire year as cash.

Student: Which credit cards are valid?
Buddy: With any credit card, you can do your payment.
 
Student: Can I make payment types other than credit card online?
Buddy: Yes, KMH or cash.

Student: How many discount are made to which bank for school payments?
Buddy: If you want to pay with it cash, there will be 6% discount.

Student: Is a payment plan created while registering online?
Buddy: Yes.

Student: When the deposit account is opened, is the account made from the bank inside the school?
Buddy: Yes.

Student: How many levels in preparation?
Buddy: There are TRACK 1, TRACK 2, TRACK 3 and TRACK 4.

Student: What happens if I fail the prep school?
Buddy: You will have to take summer school to pass prep exam.

Student: I studied preparatory school for one year in another school. Do I have to study at Kadir Has University as well?
Buddy: No.

Student: Are there classes on weekends, how many hours per week?
Buddy: No, 20 hours in a week.

Student: How many days per week of preparatory education?
Buddy: 5 days per week.

Student: If I fail the exam and do not skip the exam, will my English improve?
Buddy: Yes definetely, but it is depending on your language knowledge.

Student: How long does the preparation take, will the lessons be face-to-face?
Buddy: Yes, classes are face to face.

Student: Can a student with a Pearson certificate pass the preparation with this document?
Buddy: Yes.

Student: Is my level determined even if I do not take the exam?
Buddy: If you do not take the exam, your level cannot determined. Then you will start from the beginning.

Student: When does the preparation begin?
Buddy: You can check out this website: https://akademiktakvim.khas.edu.tr/lisans

Student: Do I have a chance to start at the lowest rate without taking the exam directly?
Buddy: Yes.

Student: How is the preparation process, are you satisfied with the teachers?
Buddy: Yes, I really loved the teachers because they always speaks English.

Student: What happens when I don't take the preparatory exam?
Buddy: You begin from the lowest degree.

Student: Is the preparation difficult?
Buddy: If you study regulary, no it is not.

Student: How many people are in the classes on average?
Buddy: Maximum 15-20 people at most.

Student: Is it possible to jump from Track 1 and 2 to the Core program?
Buddy: No, you cannot jump from Track 1 and 2 to the Core program. Track 2 is not a exit level in our program.

Student: What are the conditions for exemption from preparatory education?
Buddy: There are several ways to be exempted from Preparatory Education. You can take our university's LPPE in September or provide an English language certificate (TOEFL-IBT, CAE, PTE, etc.) (For more details: (https://my.khas.edu.tr/uploads/files/mevzuat/yabanci-diller-yuksekokulu-ingilizce-hazirlik-programi-yonergesi4.pdf -- page 2) 

Student: What day is the orientation? (The academic calendar and the dates are different in the form sent to us)
Buddy: Our university organizes orientation for newcomers after the registration dates and before the first lesson in the semester. 

Student: If we finish the preparation early, can we go to the faculty?
Buddy: Yes, then you will be irregular student.

Student: If I stay in summer school, do I have to pay a fee, I'm on a 100% scholarship.
Buddy: If you have a full scholarship, you do not have to pay for it.

Student: How much does the summer school cost?
Buddy: It changes every year.

Student: Even if my English is sufficient to pass the exam, will the preparatory program make me more comfortable with English in undergraduate?
Buddy: Yes, it will.

Student: How many tracks are there and how does this system work?
Buddy: There are 5 Tracks in total. In the fall semester, there are Track 1-2-3-4; in the spring semester, there are Track 2-3-4-5.

When you first register, you take an exam and are placed in a class of your level. Then, the process is as follows:

You are placed in Track 1,
If your overall score is above 65%, you jump to Track 3; if between 0-64%, you move to Track 2

You are placed in Track 2,
If your overall score is above 65%, you jump to Track 4; if between 45-64%, you move to Track 3; if between 0-44%, you repeat Track 2

You are placed in Track 3,
If your overall score is above 65%, you jump to Track 5; if between 45-64%, you move to Track 4; if between 0-44%, you repeat Track 3

You are placed in Track 4,
If your overall score is between 45-100%, you move to Track 5; if between 0-44%, you repeat Track 4


Student: Is the exam on paper? Is there any speaking?
Buddy: Yes, it will be on paper for the first stage. Speaking exam is in the second stage.

Student: Will my scholarship be cut?
Buddy: No, it will not be cut.

Student: What happens if we don't pass the placement test?
Buddy: You will take place in the prep class for a year.

Student: Is the preparatory calendar and the school calendar the same?
Buddy: Yes, it is same.

5bd60f46-18fe-46b4-9297-02284ba3a534.text:
Below are the questions about Kadir Has University and asked by student to the Buddy. Below, questions include questions and their answers from the student affairs, registration and exams in Kadir Has University. 

Student: Will there be a notification for online registration?
Buddy: You have to keep track of the announcements.

Student: Do you have special opportunities (financial support, dormitory, etc.) for full scholarship students?
Buddy: Yes, you can check out this website for detailed information: https://aday.khas.edu.tr/burslar

Student: When can I get my school password after online registration?
Buddy: You will take an e-mail about your student number and password right after your registration. 

Student: Is one photo enough for the record?
Buddy: Yes.

Student: Are there any advantages to enrolling face-to-face other than seeing the school?
Buddy: No.
 
Student: With whom registration can be made other than the mother and father, can the student register alone?
Buddy: You can also register yourself. However, if you are going to pay the school on credit, you must have a guarantor with you during registration.

Student: Does the high school diploma itself or its printout be required for registration?
Buddy: You can give print-out version of your diploma but you should show diploma itself as well.

Student: How about double major and minor? When can I apply?
Buddy: You can apply for double major and minor between 3rd and 6th semester. For double major, your GPA has to be minimum 2.75, for minor, your GPA has to be minimum 2.50.

Student: Where do I get the school card when I register online?
Buddy: You can take it from the student affairs.

Student: When the diploma is uploaded online, does it have to be given physically at school?
Buddy: No.

Student: In which class is the double major and minor branch applied?
Buddy: Between 3rd and 6th semester.

Student: If the department is to be changed at school, how is it done?
Buddy: You can check out for it: https://www.khas.edu.tr/yatay-gecis/

Student: Is it compulsory for the student to come for registration?
Buddy: No, you can do it online. 	

Student: How do I get my school e-mail address for online registration / face-to-face registration?
Buddy: You will receive and e-mail about your e-mail address and password.

Student: When will the mail arrive for login to Sparks system?
Buddy: Right after your registration.

Student: When and how will the user name and password for the student registration form be sent?
Buddy: It will send via e-mail.	

Student: Is it necessary to deliver the documents to the school after registering online?
Buddy: No.

Student: Is graduation certificate accepted instead of diploma for registration?
Buddy: No, you have to give your high school diploma for registration.

Student: How can I register in the Sparks system?
Buddy: You can login with your student number and password.

Student: Was it necessary to write to the top 3 choices for the ranking scholarship?
Buddy: There is no necessities for it.

Student: I don't have a school mail, what should I do?
Buddy: Your school mail adress will be send your personal mail adress. So you should not worry about it.

Student: Is registration online?
Buddy: You can do both online or face-to-face.

Student: Is there any scholarship that I can get if I am the top student of the department?
Buddy: Yes, you can check out this website for detailed information: https://aday.khas.edu.tr/burslar 

Student: Is there anything I need to do before I come to the school for registration?
Buddy: No.

Student: How can I reach student affairs?
Buddy: You can reach out by calling them or via mail adress. Here is the number for it: (0212) 533 65 32

Student: I will make my registration online, is it okay if someone else takes my student card?
Buddy: You have to take your student card.

Student: Is it possible to take the exam without a card?
Buddy: No, it is not possible.

Student: Is it okay if I get the diploma from e-government for my registration?
Buddy: A copy of the high school diploma must be uploaded to SPARKS. Barcode high school graduation certificate obtained from e-government is also valid.

Student: I won't be enrolling in the school, do I have to tell someone?
Buddy: The student can inform his/her buddy and the Student Affairs.

Student: Is there anything I need to do before I come to the school for registration?
Buddy: After the placement results are announced, the SPARKS Student Information Form must be filled.

Student: Whether there is any action to be taken from the e-government before registration.
Buddy: Information on registration from e-government is published on the link https://www.khas.edu.tr/e-devletten-kayit-islemleri/ .

Student: Is there anything I need to do in the period between registration and exam?
Buddy: No, you do not need.

Student: Are there any documents I need to physically deliver to the school after online registration?
Buddy: If there is no missing document uploaded to SPARKS, it is not necessary to come physically, but students who have not completed their high school graduation are required to submit a student certificate.

Student: I am out of the province, how can I get my student card?
Buddy: If necessary, the ID cards of the students who request can be sent to their addresses by post.

Student: When can I get my school card after online registration?	
Buddy: Those who complete the online registration process can get their student ID cards from the Security Affairs Office during the registration week, starting from the day after the registration process is finalised.
 
Student: How do I do the registration process?
Buddy: Information on registration procedures is published on the link https://www.khas.edu.tr/kayit-kabul/.

Student: Can I request and get my student ID card online through sparks?
Buddy: Student ID cards are printed without request and distributed from the Security Affairs Office.

Student: Can I get the student ID card immediately on the day I come to enrol in the school?
Buddy: Student ID cards are given immediately to those who come to the University and register in person, once the procedures are completed.

Student: Between which dates is the e-government registration?
Buddy: Information on the registration dates is published on the link https://www.khas.edu.tr/kayit-kabul/ after the announcement by ÖSYM.

Student: When can I get the student card at the latest, since online registration will be done?
Buddy: Student ID cards must be obtained before the English Placement and Proficiency Exam.

Student: Do you mind if we get the student cards on the day of the preparatory exam?
Buddy: Since you must have your student ID cards with you when you enter the exam, it is recommended that you get your card beforehand in order to avoid any delays.
